<task id="AIPU2-112" project="Spaarke AI Platform Unification R2">
  <metadata>
    <title>Capability routing benchmark (layer distribution and latency)</title>
    <phase>6</phase>
    <tags>testing, performance, routing</tags>
    <status>completed</status>
    <estimated-effort>3 hours</estimated-effort>
    <dependencies>AIPU2-061, AIPU2-066</dependencies>
    <parallel-safe>true</parallel-safe>
  </metadata>
  <prompt>
    Benchmark the CapabilityRouter (AIPU2-061) to verify that Layer distribution meets the
    design targets (greater than 60% Layer 1 fast-path, less than 10% Layer 3 full orchestration)
    and that latency budgets are met per layer. The key architectural guarantee is that exactly
    one LLM call is made per turn regardless of which layer handles it (AIPU2-066 ensures this).
    This benchmark validates both the routing heuristics and the single-LLM-call invariant
    under a realistic message corpus.
  </prompt>
  <role>Performance engineer or AI engineer with knowledge of the capability routing architecture.</role>
  <goal>
    A benchmark run of 100+ diverse test messages through CapabilityRouter produces a layer
    distribution report. Layer 1 handles greater than 60% of messages. Layer 3 handles less
    than 10%. p50 and p95 latency are measured per layer. The single-LLM-call invariant is
    confirmed for all 100+ messages. Results are documented in notes/routing-benchmark-report.md.
  </goal>
  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>projects/spaarke-ai-platform-unification-r2/design.md</file>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/Routing</file>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/Ai/Orchestration</file>
    </files>
  </knowledge>
  <steps>
    <step>Assemble a corpus of 100+ test messages representing realistic legal workspace usage: simple factual lookups (expected Layer 1), document summarization (expected Layer 2), multi-step analysis with tool use (expected Layer 3). Include edge cases and ambiguous queries.</step>
    <step>Instrument CapabilityRouter to emit telemetry: message ID, routed layer, routing decision timestamp, LLM call count, total response time. Write to a structured log file during the benchmark run.</step>
    <step>Run the 100+ message corpus through the router in a controlled environment (dev, single-threaded, no concurrent load). Collect timing and routing data.</step>
    <step>Analyze layer distribution: calculate Layer 1 %, Layer 2 %, Layer 3 % from the log. Verify Layer 1 >= 60% and Layer 3 <= 10%. If not met, review routing heuristics and adjust thresholds.</step>
    <step>Verify single-LLM-call invariant: for every message in the corpus, assert LLM call count == 1. Any message with LLM call count != 1 is a bug — document and fix.</step>
    <step>Calculate p50 and p95 latency per layer from the timing data. Compare to design targets (Layer 1: p95 < 800ms, Layer 2: p95 < 2000ms, Layer 3: p95 < 5000ms — adjust per design.md if different).</step>
    <step>Document findings in notes/routing-benchmark-report.md: corpus size, layer distribution table, latency percentiles per layer, LLM call count verification, any routing adjustments made.</step>
  </steps>
  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion>Benchmark corpus contains at least 100 diverse test messages covering all three layer types.</criterion>
    <criterion>Layer 1 handles at least 60% of corpus messages.</criterion>
    <criterion>Layer 3 handles no more than 10% of corpus messages.</criterion>
    <criterion>Every message in the corpus results in exactly one LLM call.</criterion>
    <criterion>p50 and p95 latency are measured per layer and documented.</criterion>
    <criterion>Benchmark report written to notes/routing-benchmark-report.md with distribution table and latency data.</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>
</task>
